            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Weber\u2019s story began not in San Francisco, but thousands of miles away in a Saigon orphanage. Born in the final, chaotic years of the Vietnam War, he was adopted as a toddler by a kind, working-class couple from Daly City, the Webers. Growing up, David was a quiet, observant child, loved by his adoptive parents but always conscious of the unspoken questions surrounding his origins. The German surname and his Asian features made him a puzzle he didn't try too hard to solve. His world was the fog-drenched streets of his neighborhood and the steady, practical love of his machinist father and bookkeeper mother.\n\nHe was never an academic star. While his peers aimed for Berkeley or State, David found comfort in predictability and tangible results. After graduating from high school, he followed his father\u2019s advice to take the postal service exam. The idea of a stable, union-protected job with a good pension appealed to his deep-seated need for security. Passing the exam was his most significant turning point, setting him on a path he would walk, quite literally, for the next three decades.\n\nNow 52, David is a fixture in San Francisco\u2019s Inner Richmond district. He lives alone in a rent-controlled apartment he\u2019s had for twenty years, a quiet sanctuary from the city's churn. His daily routine is a comforting rhythm: morning coffee at a small Chinese bakery on Clement Street, a short Muni ride to the post office, and then the familiar heft of his mailbag. His 1.5-mile route is his domain; he knows the families, the solitary renters, and the small business owners not by intimate conversation, but by the flow of their mail, marking time with subscription renewals and forwarded letters.\n\nA lifelong bachelor after a serious relationship fizzled out in his thirties, his connections are rooted in community rather than intimacy. He\u2019s a regular at a corner pub, where he reads the paper and exchanges brief pleasantries. San Francisco is not a city he conquered, but one he services. He has seen it gentrify and transform, watching tech millionaires move into flats once occupied by families he delivered letters to for years. His dream is simple: to retire with his pension intact and maybe, finally, take a trip to Vietnam\u2014not to find answers, but just to see the place he came from before settling into a quiet, well-earned rest."
