            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, staring at a photo of his parents\u2019 wedding on the mantelpiece. They were young, smiling, their German heritage etched in their features. He then looked at his own reflection in the glass, tracing the shape of his eyes. It wasn't sadness he felt, but a quiet recognition\u2014a puzzle piece that fit the board but didn\u2019t match the picture. This was the moment he learned to be a good observer, cementing a comfortable distance that would define him.\n\n2.\nAt nineteen, he held the thick envelope from the U.S. Postal Service. In the quiet of the Daly City kitchen, the formal job offer felt heavier than paper. It wasn't just a job; it was a map for a life that, until then, had no clear path. For a boy from a Saigon orphanage, that letter wasn't about a career, but about an anchor. It was the profound relief of a future he could finally see, a security his practical soul craved above all else.\n\n3.\nHe was thirty-five. Sarah sat on his couch, the fog pressing against the window. \"Is this enough, David?\" she asked, her voice gentle. \"This route, this apartment\u2026 this quiet?\" He had no answer. In that moment, he knew his love for routine was a wall she couldn't scale, and her desire for more was a world he couldn't enter. The silence that followed was the end. It wasn't bitter, just a quiet resignation that taught him to prefer the predictability of being alone.\n\n4.\nOn a particularly damp Inner Richmond morning, Mrs. Lim, a frail woman on 9th Avenue, was waiting at her gate. For years, he\u2019d made sure to hand her the mail directly. This time, instead of taking her letters, she pressed a small, warm thermos into his hands. She simply nodded and smiled. The jasmine tea inside warmed him more than any coat could. It was a silent acknowledgment\u2014a feeling of being woven into the fabric of the community, not just walking over it.\n\n5.\nAbout ten years ago, he held a forwarding notice for the Chen family, whose children he'd watched grow up via school report cards and birthday invitations. The next day, in that same mail slot, he placed a slick magazine for a new software company addressed to \"Current Resident.\" He felt no anger, just a profound sense of silent witness. He was the archivist of a disappearing neighborhood, his mailbag carrying the evidence of a city constantly replacing its families with new ambitions."
